# Hephaestus Network (Cursor adapter)

Cursor ships `/hep-build`, `/hep-network`, and
`/hep-cloud` as commands (see `cursor/plugin/`); this rule is the
fallback adapter so plain-text routing triggers work too: when the user writes
`/hep-network <request>` or `@Hephaestus <request>`, do the following.

1. Resolve the runner — first executable wins:
   `~/.agentlas/runtime/current/bin/hephaestus`, `./bin/hephaestus` in the
   workspace, or the newest
   `~/.claude/plugins/cache/agentlas-core-engine/hephaestus/*/bin/hephaestus`
   (sort -V). If none exists, tell the user to run the one-touch installer:
   `curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/agentlas-ai/Hephaestus/v0.7.10/scripts/install-all-runtimes.sh | bash`

2. Run `"$RUNNER" auth ensure --timeout 180` first. It opens the default
   browser only on first use and silently reuses an existing Agentlas saved
   sign-in.

3. Run `"$RUNNER" route "<request>" --runtime cursor` in the terminal and act
   on the JSON decision:
   - `route`: report the selected card, then invoke the agent with the
     original request.
   - `clarify`: ask the `clarify_question` with the candidates.
   - `pipeline`: execute `stages` in order, saving artifacts under
     `handoff_dir`; stop and report on any stage failure.
   - `hub_fallback`/`hub_candidates`: Hub lookup used redacted keywords only;
     the raw prompt and local memory were not sent.
   - `propose_new`: offer to build a new agent via the Hephaestus meta-agent.
   - `refuse`: explain the reasons; do not work around loop guards.

4. Hard rules: the router only chooses an agent or fetches a BYOM Hub bundle.
   Actual tool execution follows Cursor's safety and permission model.
